ers, competitors, and market conditions to inform business decisions. It provides insights into market trends, customer preferences, and competitive dynamics. This process can be based on primary or secondary data and is used to assess the potential success of new product launches. By understanding consumers' needs and preferences, companies can make informed decisions about product development and marketing strategies. Market Research serves as an external source of valuable information that helps businesses navigate the competitive landscape effectively.\n3. SENSITIVITY ANALYSIS, Sensitivity analysis calculates how responsive a decision is to changes in any of the variables used to calculate it.\nRelationships\n\nid,source,target,description\n10,FOCUS GROUP,MARKET RESEARCH,Focus group is related to market research. They are both research techniques to deal with uncertainty.\n11,MARKET RESEARCH,FOCUS GROUP,Market research is related to focus group. They are both research techniques to deal with uncertainty.\n\nOutput:\n{{\n    \"title\": \"Chapter 8: Risk and Uncertainty\",\n    \"summary\": \"Chapter 8 covers the following Learning Outcomes. C. Decision-Making Techniques 6. Dealing with risk and uncertainty in decision making a) Suggest research techniques to reduce uncertainty (e.g. focus groups, market research). b) Explain the use of simulation, expected values and sensitivity. c) Apply expected values and sensitivity to decision-making problems. d) Apply the techniques of maximax, maximin and minimax regret to decision-making problems, including the production of profit tables. e) Interpret a decision tree and use it to solve a multi-stage decision problem. f) Calculate the value of perfect and imperfect information. \",\n    \"rating\": 7.0,\n    \"rating_explanation\": \"The impact severity rating is high due to the fundamental importance of bookkeeping in accounting.\",\n    \"findings\": [\n        {{\n            \"summary\": \"Focus groups and market research are important research techniques to reduce uncertainty\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Companies often use focus groups and/or market research to deal with uncertainty. Focus groups are used to reduce uncertainty about new products by gathering opinions from a group of people in an interactive environment. Participants are chosen at random and may be observed by marketing professionals. Market Research involves the systematic gathering and analyzing of data about consumers, competitors, and market conditions to inform business decisions. It provides insights into market trends, customer preferences, and competitive dynamics. This process can be based on primary or secondary data and is used to assess the potential success of new product launches. By understanding consumers' needs and preferences, companies can make informed decisions about product development and marketing strategies. Market Research serves as an external source of valuable information that helps businesses navigate the competitive landscape effectively. [Data: Concepts (1, 2); Relationships (10, 11)]\"\n        }},\n        {{\n            \"summary\": \"Explain and apply sensitivity analysis to decision-making problems\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Sensitivity analysis calculates how responsive a decision is to changes in any of the variables used in making that decision. It looks at one variable at a time and measures how much the variable can change by (in percentage terms) before affecting the decision. The smaller the percentage, the more sensitive the decision is to that variable. Sensitivity % = Profit/Variable  [Data: Concepts (3)]\"\n        }}\n    ]\n}}\n\n# Real Data\n\nUse the following text for your answer. Do not make anything up in your answer.\n\nText:\n-----Entities-----\nhuman_readable_id,title,description,degree\n904,\"\"\"LEARNING RATE\"\"\",\"The \"\"Learning Rate\"\" refers to the rate at which workers improve their efficiency and reduce the time taken to complete tasks as they gain experience. It is a measure of how quickly production efficiency improves as more units are produced. Specifically, it indicates the rate at which labour time per unit decreases as workers become more efficient with experience. In the context of Bokco, a 90% learning rate was initially used, meaning that the time taken to produce a unit decreases by 10% with each doubling of the number of units produced. However, an engineer later suggested an 85% learning rate, indicating a more rapid improvement in efficiency.\",10\n1813,\"\"\"LABOUR EFFICIENCY PLANNING VARIANCE\"\"\",\"\"\"Labour efficiency planning variance\"\" arises when the standard hours need to be revised due to factors beyond the control of operational managers, such as changes in employment legislation, customer demands for higher quality, or incorrect estimates of the learning effect. It is calculated as the difference between the standard hours for actual production and the revised hours for actual production, multiplied by the standard rate.\",3\n1029,\"\"\"RE-CALCULATED LABOUR EFFICIENCY VARIANCE\"\"\",\"\"\"Re-calculated labour efficiency variance = Actual labour hours * Standard rate - Standard hours for actual production (taking into account the learning rate) * Standard rate\"\"\",2\n1814,\"\"\"LABOUR EFFICIENCY OPERATIONAL VARIANCE\"\"\",\"\"\"Labour efficiency operational variance is calculated as (Revised hours for actual production - actual hours for actual production) * standard rate.\"\"\",2\n905,\"\"\"LABOUR TIME FOR THE 30TH AND SUBSEQUENT UNITS\"\"\",\"\"\"Labour time for the 30th and subsequent units is calculated as the difference between the total time taken to make the first 30 units and the total time taken to make the first 29 units, resulting in 0.347 hours.\"\"\",2\n1810,\"\"\"REVISING LABOUR STANDARDS AND ANALYZING VARIANCES FOR BOKCO'S NEW PRODUCT\"\"\",\"\"\"Bokco, a manufacturing company, relies on temporary workers and uses cost-plus pricing. The company began production of a new product with a standard cost card for labor. The production manager realized that a learning rate of 90% should have been anticipated. The revised standard time for the first 460 units was calculated based on this learning rate.\"\"\",2\n907,\"\"\"ESTIMATING THE LEARNING RATE\"\"\",\"\"\"Estimating the learning rate involves using a tabular approach based on production to date and the time taken, especially when cumulative units are given in exponentials of 2. The learning rate stops when the incremental time per unit becomes constant.\"\"\",1\n908,\"\"\"QUIZ: LEARNING RATE\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz involves calculating the learning rate that applied to the new PC and estimating the point at which the learning period finishes, based on the incremental time taken for each unit.\"\"\",1\n912,\"\"\"QUIZ: EXPECTED AND ACTUAL LEARNING RATES\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz involves calculating the actual learning rate experienced by Go Fast Cars in manufacturing a new model of its 'lightning' sports car. The quiz compares the budgeted and actual cumulative total times for the first 16 units and requires calculating the actual learning rate and suggesting reasons for the discrepancy.\"\"\",1\n903,\"\"\"QUIZ: LEARNING CURVE AND STEADY STATE\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz involves calculating the labour time per unit for the 30th and subsequent units and the total labour time to make the first 100 units of the XY123 model, considering a learning rate of 85%.\"\"\",1\n1005,\"\"\"PLANNING AND OPERATIONAL VARIANCES\"\"\",\"\"\"Planning and operational variances\"\" are utilized to calculate a revised budget, identify and explain factors that could and could not be allowed to revise an original budget, and calculate, identify the cause of, and explain variances for sales, materials, and labor. These variances are instrumental in distinguishing between those caused by changes in planning assumptions and those resulting from operational performance. They help in identifying whether variances are due to external factors or internal inefficiencies, thereby providing a comprehensive understanding of the underlying reasons for budget deviations.\",5\n1006,\"\"\"BUDGET REVISIONS\"\"\",\"\"\"BUDGET REVISIONS\"\" form a critical component of performance management systems. Initially, a budget is established to serve as a benchmark against which an organization's actual results can be compared to assess performance. While changes to the budget can be permitted under certain circumstances, these revisions must be meticulously controlled to prevent potential abuse. The process of revising budgets involves identifying factors that justify a revision and those that do not, as well as applying specific principles to ensure the integrity of the budgetary process. This topic is explored in a quiz that includes questions about the criteria for revising an original budget and the principles that should guide such revisions.\",2\n1007,\"\"\"PRINCIPLES OF BUDGET REVISIONS\"\"\",\"\"\"The principles of budget revisions include revising the budget if something occurred during the budget period that was outside the control of the manager, not revising budgets to hide inefficiencies, and ensuring that senior management approves only appropriate revisions.\"\"\",2\n1876,\"\"\"LABOUR RATE OPERATIONAL VARIANCE\"\"\",\"\"\"Labour rate operational variance compares the revised standard rate per hour to the actual rate per hour and multiplies the difference by the number of hours worked.\"\"\",1\n1875,\"\"\"MATERIALS PRICE PLANNING VARIANCE\"\"\",\"\"\"Materials price planning variance compares the original standard price to the revised standard price and multiplies the difference by the actual quantity of material used.\"\"\",1\n906,\"\"\"TOTAL LABOUR TIME FOR THE FIRST 100 UNITS\"\"\",\"\"\"Total labour time for the first 100 units is calculated as the sum of the total time taken to make the first 30 units and the time taken to make the next 70 units, resulting in 37.80 hours.\"\"\",1\n\n\n-----Relationships-----\nhuman_readable_id,source,target,description,rank\n804,\"\"\"LEARNING RATE\"\"\",\"\"\"LABOUR EFFICIENCY VARIANCES\"\"\",\"\"\"The learning rate affects the calculation of labour efficiency variances, as seen in Bokco's case where variances were calculated based on both 90% and 85% learning rates.\"\"\",14\n805,\"\"\"LEARNING RATE\"\"\",\"\"\"LABOUR EFFICIENCY PLANNING VARIANCE\"\"\",\"\"\"Learning rate affects Labour efficiency planning variance as it influences the standard hours for actual production.\"\"\",13\n926,\"\"\"LABOUR EFFICIENCY VARIANCE\"\"\",\"\"\"RE-CALCULATED LABOUR EFFICIENCY VARIANCE\"\"\",\"\"\"Labour efficiency variance is recalculated to take into account the learning rate.\"\"\",13\n806,\"\"\"LEARNING RATE\"\"\",\"\"\"LABOUR EFFICIENCY OPERATIONAL VARIANCE\"\"\",\"\"\"Learning rate affects Labour efficiency operational variance as it influences the revised hours for actual production.\"\"\",12\n798,\"\"\"LEARNING RATE\"\"\",\"\"\"LABOUR TIME FOR THE 30TH AND SUBSEQUENT UNITS\"\"\",\"\"\"Labour time for the 30th and subsequent units is calculated based on the learning rate of 85%.\"\"\",12\n802,\"\"\"LEARNING RATE\"\"\",\"\"\"RE-CALCULATED LABOUR EFFICIENCY VARIANCE\"\"\",\"\"\"Learning rate is used in the recalculation of Labour efficiency variance.\"\"\",12\n803,\"\"\"LEARNING RATE\"\"\",\"\"\"REVISING LABOUR STANDARDS AND ANALYZING VARIANCES FOR BOKCO'S NEW PRODUCT\"\"\",\"\"\"The case of revising labour standards and analyzing variances for Bokco's new product involves the concept of learning rate, initially set at 90% and later suggested to be 85%.\"\"\",12\n799,\"\"\"LEARNING RATE\"\"\",\"\"\"ESTIMATING THE LEARNING RATE\"\"\",\"\"\"Estimating the Learning Rate involves calculating the learning rate based on production data and time taken.\"\"\",11\n800,\"\"\"LEARNING RATE\"\"\",\"\"\"QUIZ: LEARNING RATE\"\"\",\"\"\"The quiz on Learning Rate involves calculating the learning rate and estimating the point at which the learning period finishes.\"\"\",11\n801,\"\"\"LEARNING RATE\"\"\",\"\"\"QUIZ: EXPECTED AND ACTUAL LEARNING RATES\"\"\",\"\"\"The Quiz: Expected and Actual Learning Rates involves calculating the actual learning rate experienced by Go Fast Cars and comparing it to the expected learning rate.\"\"\",11\n797,\"\"\"QUIZ: LEARNING CURVE AND STEADY STATE\"\"\",\"\"\"LEARNING RATE\"\"\",\"\"\"The quiz on Learning Curve and Steady State involves calculating the labour time per unit and total labour time, considering a learning rate of 85%.\"\"\",11\n990,\"\"\"PLANNING AND OPERATIONAL VARIANCES\"\"\",\"\"\"LABOUR EFFICIENCY PLANNING VARIANCE\"\"\",\"\"\"Labour efficiency planning variance is a type of planning and operational variance used to assess performance against labor efficiency expectations.\"\"\",8\n987,\"\"\"PLANNING AND OPERATIONAL VARIANCES\"\"\",\"\"\"BUDGET REVISIONS\"\"\",\"\"\"Planning and Operational Variances involve Budget Revisions.\"\"\",7\n986,\"\"\"PLANNING AND OPERATIONAL VARIANCES\"\"\",\"\"\"PRINCIPLES OF BUDGET REVISIONS\"\"\",\"\"\"Planning and Operational Variances include the Principles of Budget Revisions.\"\"\",7\n989,\"\"\"PLANNING AND OPERATIONAL VARIANCES\"\"\",\"\"\"LABOUR RATE OPERATIONAL VARIANCE\"\"\",\"\"\"Labour rate operational variance is a type of planning and operational variance used to assess performance against labor cost expectations.\"\"\",6\n988,\"\"\"PLANNING AND OPERATIONAL VARIANCES\"\"\",\"\"\"MATERIALS PRICE PLANNING VARIANCE\"\"\",\"\"\"Materials price planning variance is a type of planning and operational variance used to assess performance against material cost expectations.\"\"\",6\n1658,\"\"\"REVISING LABOUR STANDARDS AND ANALYZING VARIANCES FOR BOKCO'S NEW PRODUCT\"\"\",\"\"\"LABOUR EFFICIENCY VARIANCES\"\"\",\"\"\"The case of revising labour standards and analyzing variances for Bokco's new product involves calculating labour efficiency variances based on different learning rates.\"